---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Isophotal analysis";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Isophotal analysis</h1>

    <p>
      <strong>Isophotal analysis</strong> measures the radial profiles of galaxy light distribution by fitting concentric ellipses to isophotes (contours of constant surface brightness). Derived parameters include position angle (θ), ellipticity (ε), and higher-order Fourier moments (a₄/a boxiness).
    </p>

    <h2>Physical interpretation</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Position angle twists:</strong> Variations in PA across radius can indicate triaxiality or projection effects from viewing a non-spherical system at an angle.</li>
      <li><strong>Ellipticity:</strong> Measures the flattening of isophotes; related to intrinsic geometry and viewing angle.</li>
      <li><strong>Boxiness (a₄/a):</strong> Deviations from perfect ellipses; negative values (boxy) may indicate triaxiality or embedded bars; positive values (disky) trace disk-like or edge-on structures.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Application to dwarf galaxies</h2>
    <p>
      Watkins et al. (2026) apply isophotal analysis to 193 dwarf galaxies and find that traditional isophotal parameters show limited discriminatory power for dwarf morphological classification compared to more massive galaxies<sup><a href="/pages/watkins_2026_isophote_dwarf_structure">1</a></sup>. They argue that dwarf galaxy structures are self-similar in this parameter space, necessitating higher-dimensional statistical approaches.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Watkins A. E., et al. (2026). arXiv:2603.11166.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
